A debugging story about prototypes, proxies, and one invariant that refused to budge
Introduction
This story starts with a dropdown that said “No results.”
Press enter or click to view image in full size

demo of the issueWeird. No error banner, no red text in the console pointing anywhere. The network tab looked healthy: 200s everywhere, the API returning exactly the data it should.
Yet that data never made it to the screen. A backend problem, maybe? Everything on that side checked out, and nothing had changed there anyway. Something was off. The only thing is that recharts had been recently updated and under the hood immer with it 👀.
First, what is Immer, and why does everyone use it?
If you’ve written React or Redux code in the last several years, you’ve almost certainly used Immer, even if you didn’t know it. It gets downloaded more than 50 million times a week.
In JavaScript, we often need to update state immutably: produce a brand-new object instead of changing the old one in place. This matters a lot in React and Redux, because they detect changes by comparing object references. If you mutate the old object, the reference doesn’t change, and nothing re-renders.
The trouble is that immutable updates in plain JavaScript are genuinely painful:
// Updating one nested field, immutably, by hand:
const next = {
…state,
user: {
…state.user,
settings: {
…state.user.settings,
theme: "dark",
},
},
};That’s a lot of spread operators just to change one value, and it’s easy to get wrong. Immer lets you write this instead:
import { produce } from "immer";const next = produce(state, (draft) => {
draft.user.settings.theme = "dark";
});
You get a function called produce, you’re handed a draft, and you just… mutate it. Immer watches what you touch and hands you back a correctly-updated, immutable copy, sharing all the parts you didn’t change. It’s wonderful.
This is exactly why Redux Toolkit uses Immer under the hood. When you write a reducer in RTK and “mutate” state, you’re actually mutating an Immer draft. That’s the magic that makes RTK reducers so pleasant.
Inside RTK case reducers created with createSlice or createReducer, draftable object state is exposed as an Immer draft, state is an Immer draft. It’ll matter a lot in a minute.
The security fix that started all this
In version 11.1.9, the Immer maintainers shipped a security patch. Their concern was a classic JavaScript attack called prototype pollution, and it looked something like this:
produce({}, (draft) => {
draft.constructor.prototype.isAdmin = true;
});The worry: if user-controlled data could reach a line like that, an attacker could write a property onto Object.prototype (which every object in your program inherits from), and suddenly every object in the app claims isAdmin === true. That’s a real and scary class of bug.
So the fix tried to lock down access to constructor and __proto__ on drafts. Good instinct! Prototype pollution is nasty, and the maintainers were trying to protect millions of people. Reading the patch, it totally made sense.
But to understand what went wrong, we need to slow down and look at two pieces of machinery: prototypes and proxies.
Prototypes
Every JavaScript object has a hidden link to another object, called its prototype— every object except one. At the very top of the chain sits Object.prototype, the “mother object” that everything else inherits from, and its prototype is null. That’s where the walk stops. When you ask for a property that an object doesn’t have itself, JavaScript walks up this chain looking for it, all the way to Object.prototype, and gives up at null.
`const obj = {};
obj.toString; // obj doesn't have `toString`… but Object.prototype doesThat link is why obj.toString() works even though you never defined it. A plain object’s prototype is Object.prototype, and that’s where shared methods like toString, hasOwnProperty, and the property constructor live.
Two facts that are the whole story here:
Fact 1: obj.constructor isn’t stored on obj. It’s inherited from Object.prototype, and it points back at the Object function itself.
({}).constructor === Object; // trueFact 2: Object is a function, and constructor-capable functions generally have a prototype; arrow and bound functions do not. Crucially, the Object function’s prototype property is special. The language marks it as non-configurable and non-writable:
Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(Object, "prototype");
// { value: {…}, writable: false, enumerable: false, configurable: false }Remember those conjunctions: non-configurable, non-writable.

• Non-writable means the value can’t be reassigned: Object.prototype = somethingElse will never work.

• Non-configurable means the property can’t be deleted or redefined; you can’t even use Object.defineProperty to change your mind later. Together they’re the language’s way of saying this property is permanent, exactly as it is. That permanence is the trap this whole bug springs.
Proxies
A Proxy is an object that wraps another object and lets you intercept operations on it. You provide “traps”: little functions that run when someone reads a property, writes one, checks in, and so on.
const wrapped = new Proxy(target, {
get(obj, key) {
console.log("someone read", key);
return obj[key];
},
});For those who are familiar with middleware, if a middleware can be considered as a “checkpoint”, a proxy is more of a “disguise”: wrapped impersonates target (consumers can’t tell it is a proxy) while intercepting low-level operations like reads, writes, and in checks. That’s how Immer drafts work: the get trap hands back nested drafts, while the set trap records mutations.

