But a proxy can’t lie about everything. JavaScript enforces proxy invariants that keep its answers consistent with the target. One says:
If the target has an own property that is non-configurable and non-writable, the get trap must return that property’s real value. No substitutions.
That’s the trap: the built-in Object function’s prototype property is non-configurable and non-writable. If a proxy around that function returns a fake prototype, the engine throws — protecting the language’s own integrity.
The bug: Who Reads constructor.prototype, Anyway?
Now we can look at what 11.1.9 actually did. To block draft.constructor.prototype access, it added a get trap that wrapped constructor in another proxy — one designed to hand back a harmless empty object instead of the real prototype:
// simplified from the 11.1.9 change
get(state, prop) {
if (prop === "constructor" || prop === "__proto__") {
const value = latest(state)[prop]; return new Proxy(value, {
get(target, key) {
if (key === "prototype" || key === "__proto__") {
return Object.freeze(Object.create(null)); // a fake, safe prototype
}
return Reflect.get(target, key);
},
});
}
}
Let’s take a look at that inner get trap carefully. When someone reads .prototype, it returns a fake frozen object.
But what did we wrap? We wrapped value, which is draft.constructor — and on a draft, that’s the real Object function. And Object.prototype is non-configurable and non-writable.
So the moment anything reads draft.constructor.prototype, the inner proxy tries to return the fake object, the engine checks the invariant, and:
TypeError: 'get' on proxy: property 'prototype' is a read-only and
non-configurable data property on the proxy target but the proxy did not
return its actual value (expected '#<Object>' but got '[object Object]')The fix couldn’t do the thing it was written to do. The language simply forbids it. That’s the part that fascinates me about this bug: no amount of cleverness in the implementation could have made this approach work. The spec itself was standing in the way.
The blast radius: RTK + Lodash
Who reads constructor.prototype? Lodash does. Constantly. Deep inside utilities like _.isEmpty and _.isEqual, Lodash has a helper called isPrototype:
function isPrototype(value) {
const Ctor = value.constructor;
const proto = (typeof Ctor === "function" && Ctor.prototype) || objectProto;
return value === proto;
}There it is again: Ctor.prototype. Completely innocent code. It’s just trying to figure out whether an object is a prototype object. It has done this reliably for a decade.
Now put the pieces together with what we said earlier: inside an RTK reducer, state is an Immer draft. So this ordinary-looking reducer becomes a landmine:
setUsersFilters(state, action) {
const currentFilters = state.availableFilters.usersFilters; // a draft if (_.isEmpty(currentFilters)) { // reads constructor.prototype → 💥
// …
}
state.availableFilters.usersFilters = action.payload;
}
_.isEmpty threw inside the reducer, so the mutation never ran, the data never reached the store (in RTK you either update the store or you don’t), and the UI showed “No results” despite a successful API response. RTK wise, this was a thunk throwing, so no changes to apply. It looked like a backend problem, but the state update had died in the reducer.
And nobody upgraded Immer directly. A routine recharts bump consolidated a shared dependency range and silently moved the app from Immer v10 to v11.1.9 — an invisible dependency change with very visible consequences.
The key insight: the guard could only protect by breaking valid code
One question unlocked everything: on a draft, is draft.constructor.prototype even something Immer can protect?
produce({ data: {} }, (draft) => {
draft.data.constructor === Object; // true
draft.data.constructor.prototype === Object.prototype; // true
});The real Object. The real Object.prototype. So draft.constructor.prototype.x = 1 is just a long-winded way of writing Object.prototype.x = 1, and that’s plain JavaScript any function in your program can already run, Immer or no Immer. The guard did prevent the mutation: but only by throwing whenever code read constructor.prototype, including legitimate code such as Lodash. It could not provide transparent protection while preserving normal JavaScript behavior.
One half of the patch survives scrutiny, though: draft.__proto__ resolves to Object.prototype, a plain object with no forbidden prototype property to lie about. Wrapping it is legal, and it genuinely blocks draft.__proto__.x = 1. Two halves of one patch: one that couldn’t work in principle, and one that quietly does.
The Fix I Proposed
I filed an issue with a minimal repro and the root cause, plus a PR that:

• keeps the __proto__ guard

• drops the constructor wrapper, so constructor === Object again,

• drops two smaller blocks that made 'constructor' in draft return false and silently discarded writes to keys named constructor or prototype.
Bonus: the same diagnosis explained three open issues that looked unrelated: the _.isEmpty crash, an identical _.isEqual crash , and an equality regression involving fast-deep-equal.
In the end, the maintainer confirmed the diagnosis and reverted the constructor guard in the next release. It’s the smallest, safest diff for a library with fifty million weekly downloads. Within days, the crash was gone for everyone.
Lessons Learned
Silent failures live in reducers. A throwing reducer means the store just… doesn’t update. Empty UI next to a healthy API? Breakpoint the reducer before you blame the backend.
Proxies can’t lie about everything. Proxy invariants are the spec corner you can ignore for years — until the day you can’t.
Some fixes are outright impossible. When a guard can’t work in principle, say so with a one-line proof instead of piling on workarounds.
Tests should tell “handled” apart from “threw.” The patch shipped green because its tests wrapped every attack in a try/catch that treated a crash and a successful defense the same way. I’ve written tests like that too; they hide exactly the failures you need to see.
